Title : George Thornhill (cricketer)
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}
{{Use British English|date=March 2016}}
'''George Thornhill''' (10 August 1811 – 4 February 1875) was an English [[cricket]]er with [[Amateur status in first-class cricket|amateur status]] who was active from 1831 to 1836. He was born in England and died in [[Folkestone]]. He made his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut in 1831 and appeared in seven matches as an unknown [[handedness]] [[batting (cricket)|batsman]] whose [[bowling (cricket)|bowling style]] is unknown, playing for [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge University]]. He scored 59 [[run (cricket)|runs]] with a highest score of 11 and took four [[wicket]]s.<ref name="CA37">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/37/37801/37801.html |publisher=''CricketArchive'' |title=George Thornhill |accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> 
Thornhill was the eldest son of [[George Thornhill (MP)|George Thornhill]] (1783–1852), a Huntingdonshire landowner who became [[Member of the UK Parliament|Member of Parliament]] for [[Huntingdonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Huntingdonshire]] from 1837 to his death in 1852. He was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and [[St John's College, Cambridge]]. He was [[High Sheriff of Huntingdonshire]] in 1869.<ref>{{acad |id=THRL830G |name=Thornhill, George}}</ref>

Several of his family were also cricketers: his brother [[Charles Thornhill]] played in first-class matches for Cambridge University, while another brother [[John Thornhill|John]] appeared twice in first-class games for the Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC); other brothers, and his three sons, played in minor matches.

